# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: indonesia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:indonesia/1000000000000000-number-p01] This list contains selected positive numbers in increasing order of magnitude, including counts of things, dimensionless quantities, and probabilities.
[src:indonesia/1000000000000000-number-p01] Each number is given a name in the short scale, which is used in English-speaking countries, as well as a name in the long scale, which is used in some of the countries that do not have English as their national language.
[src:indonesia/1000000000000000-number-p01] (100000; one hundred thousand or a lakh).
[src:indonesia/10th-brics-summit] The **2018 BRICS summit** is the tenth annual BRICS summit, an international relations conference attended by the heads of state or heads of government of the five member states of BRICS at the time: Brazil, Russia, India, China and South Africa.
[src:indonesia/10th-brics-summit] The summit was held in Johannesburg, South Africa, the second time that South Africa has hosted the summit with the first being the 2013 summit.
[src:indonesia/10th-brics-summit] Convened with the theme of "*BRICS in Africa: Collaboration for Inclusive Growth and Shared Prosperity in the 4th Industrial Revolution*", the next BRICS Summit set to take place in Brazil, have enjoyed the full support of the other member states along with its Chairship in 2019.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] The end of the Cold War and the subsequent violent breakup of Yugoslavia, one of the founding and core members, seemed to bring into question the very existence of the movement, yet it was preserved during the times of crisis by the pragmatic chairmanship of Indonesia.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] The summit concluded that the NAM would create a special panel of economists and experts to investigate appropriate options for debt relief needed by many member states.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] Brunei Darussalam joined the movement at the Jakarta Conference.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] Alongside Brunei, Myanmar (which left the NAM in 1979), the Philippines and Uzbekistan also joined the movement.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] Cambodia had returned, as the country was now governed by the United Nations Transitional Authority in Cambodia, while Argentina left the movement, bringing the list of members to 108 countries in total.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] Thailand as well as newly independent Armenia and Croatia were granted observer status for the first time (in total there was 8 observers), Bosnia and Herzegovina and Slovenia were granted guest status for the first time (in total there were 18 States and 13 organizations with that status).
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] Requests by Kyrgyzstan and FYR Macedonia were referred for further consideration.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] At the time of the Breakup of Yugoslavia in the early 1990s, the Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia was at the end of its 1989–1992 chairmanship of the movement and was about to transfer its chairmanship to Indonesia.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] The Yugoslav crisis created logistical and legal issues for the transfer to Indonesian chairmanship.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] At the time of the September 1–6, 1992 conference in Jakarta, the Yugoslav Wars had begun.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] Former Yugoslav republics of Croatia, Slovenia and Bosnia-Herzegovina joined the United Nations as new member states while the UN imposed sanctions against Yugoslavia.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] The new Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (consisting of Serbia and Montenegro) claimed to be the sole legal successor of Yugoslavia (which had been rejected in the United Nations Security Council Resolution 777 a couple of days following the conference).
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] The Non-Aligned Movement was unable to influence developments in Yugoslavia in any significant way and was mostly responding to them.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] The Yugoslav Crisis created an unprecedented situation in which the chairperson of the movement (Dobrica Ćosić who was in London at the time) was absent from the conference to transfer the chairmanship to Indonesia.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] The Yugoslav delegation, without any clear instructions from Belgrade, was led by Montenegrin diplomat Branko Lukovac.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] The delegation agreed that the new post-Yugoslav states could participate in the meeting with the status of observers despite the fact that Belgrade did not recognize them at the time.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] In the partially chaotic circumstances, the Yugoslav delegation (de facto Serbian and Montenegrin delegation) managed to achieve results which the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Egypt, Amr Moussa, described as good for Yugoslavia and better than what should be expected from the United Nations.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] The movement decided not to expel Yugoslavia.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] Instead, it retained the Yugoslav nametag and the *empty chair*, which was kept until the beginning of the 21st century when, after the overthrow of Slobodan Milošević, the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia dropped its claim on sole successor of Yugoslavia.
[src:indonesia/10th-summit-of-the-non-aligned-movement] The Federal Republic of Yugoslavia was not invited to conferences unless Yugoslav issues were discussed.
[src:indonesia/11th-brics-summit] The **2019 BRICS summit** was the eleventh annual BRICS summit, an international relations conference to be attended by the heads of state or heads of government of the five member states Brazil, Russia, India, China and South Africa.
[src:indonesia/11th-brics-summit] The meeting was held at the Itamaraty Palace, where the Brazilian Ministry of Foreign Affairs is located.
[src:indonesia/11th-brics-summit] The Brazilian capital hosted the BRICS summit for the second time.
[src:indonesia/11th-brics-summit] The Sherpa meeting was held in the Brazilian city of Curitiba between March 14 and 15.
[src:indonesia/11th-brics-summit] The name of the chosen theme was: *BRICS: economic growth for an innovative future*.
[src:indonesia/62] For landline area codes, the digit "0" is added before the area code when dialing domestic long distance from within Indonesia, but is always omitted when calling from abroad.
[src:indonesia/62] Instead, callers would use the Indonesian country code +62, followed by the area code, without the "0".
[src:indonesia/62] Domestic phone numbers in large cities have 8 digits, and in other areas 7 digits.
[src:indonesia/62] Mobile phone numbers have 9 to 11 digits for postpaid services, depending on the operator, whereas prepaid services have 10 to 12 digits, determined by the operator.
[src:indonesia/62] Until October 1999, East Timor was included in the Indonesian telephone numbering plan, using the area codes 0390 (for Dili) and 0399 (for Baucau).
[src:indonesia/62] For calls to landlines, callers dial +62, followed by the area code and subscriber's number, omitting the '0', hence a number in Jakarta would be dialled as +62 21-xxxx-xxxx.
[src:indonesia/62] On business cards and other contact information, telephone numbers might be listed as "HP" or "hunting".
[src:indonesia/62] "HP" is an abbreviation for "hand phone" or mobile phone and is pronounced "hah péh".
[src:indonesia/62] Hand phones might also be referred to as *pon-sel* (short form of *telepon seluler*) or *telepon genggam* ("hold-in-the-hand telephone").
[src:indonesia/62] Hunting refers to line hunting, an office line in which multiple individual lines are connected so that an incoming call can roll over to another line if the first line is busy.
[src:indonesia/62] This permits only one number to be published.
[src:indonesia/62] Numbering for FWA CDMA follows the PSTN rules (area code)-XXXX-XXXX.
[src:indonesia/62] Which X depends on the empty slot of the numbering plan, and may vary between cities.
[src:indonesia/62] These are area codes for the provinces of Jakarta, Banten, West Java, Yogyakarta, and Central Java.
[src:indonesia/62] These are area codes for the provinces of East Java, Bali, West Nusa Tenggara, and East Nusa Tenggara.
[src:indonesia/62] These are area codes for the provinces of West Sulawesi, South Sulawesi, Central Sulawesi, South East Sulawesi, North Sulawesi, and Gorontalo.
[src:indonesia/62] These are area codes for the provinces of West Kalimantan, Central Kalimantan, South Kalimantan, East Kalimantan, and North Kalimantan.
[src:indonesia/62] These are area codes for the Provinces of Aceh and North Sumatra.
[src:indonesia/62] These are area codes for the Provinces of West Sumatra, Riau, Riau Islands, Jambi, South Sumatra, Bengkulu, Bangka-Belitung, and Lampung.
[src:indonesia/62] These are area codes for the provinces of Maluku, North Maluku, Papua, Central Papua, Highland Papua, South Papua, Southwest Papua, and West Papua.
[src:indonesia/id] On 11 March 2013, PANDI approved the adoption of a new *desa* second level domain for Indonesia's 72,944 villages with autonomy for local affairs.
[src:indonesia/id] As of 17 August 2014, second-level domain registrations have entered general availability, allowing registrations to be made directly under .id, without a prefix.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The Indonesian archipelago has been inhabited since prehistoric times, with early human presence evidenced by fossils of *Homo erectus* and *Homo sapiens*, and megalithic sites.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] By the early second millennium, it had become a crossroads for international trade linking East and South Asia.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Over the centuries, external influences—including Hinduism, Buddhism and later Islam—were absorbed into local societies, which introduced lasting cultural and religious influences.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] European powers later competed to monopolise trade in the Spice Islands of Maluku during the Age of Discovery, followed by three and a half centuries of Dutch colonial rule, before Indonesia proclaimed its independence in the aftermath of World War II.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Since independence, Indonesia has experienced separatist conflicts, corruption, political upheaval and natural disasters, alongside democratisation and rapid economic growth.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The country today is a presidential republic with an elected legislature and consists of 38 provinces, some of which enjoy greater autonomy than others.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Home to over 280 million people, Indonesia ranks fourth in the world by population and has the largest Muslim population of any country.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] More than half of Indonesians live on Java, the most heavily populated island in the world, while the capital Jakarta is the world's most populous city.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesian society comprises hundreds of ethnic and linguistic groups, with Javanese forming the largest.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] National identity is unified under the motto *Bhinneka Tunggal Ika*, reflected by a national language alongside cultural and religious pluralism.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] A newly industrialised country, Indonesia has the largest national economy in Southeast Asia by GDP.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The country is active in regional and global affairs as a middle power and is a member of major multilateral organisations, including the United Nations, G20, the Non-Aligned Movement, ASEAN, and the Organisation of Islamic Cooperation.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The name *Indonesia* is usually explained as a compound of the Greek words *Indos* (Ἰνδός) and nesos (νῆσος), together meaning 'Indian islands'.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The term dates to the 19th century, well before the formation of independent Indonesia.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In 1850, George Windsor Earl, an English ethnologist, proposed the terms *Indunesians*—and his preferred term, *Malayunesians*—for the inhabitants of the "Indian Archipelago or Malay Archipelago".
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In the same publication, James Richardson Logan used *Indonesia* as a geographical term for the *Indian Archipelago*.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Dutch academics writing in East Indies publications were reluctant to adopt *Indonesia*.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] They preferred *Malay Archipelago* (Dutch: *Maleische Archipel*); the *Netherlands East Indies* (*Nederlandsch Oost Indië*), popularly *Indië*; *the East* (*de Oost*); and *Insulinde*.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] After 1900, *Indonesia* became more common in academic circles outside the Netherlands, and native nationalist groups adopted it for political expression.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Adolf Bastian of the University of Berlin popularised the name through his book *Indonesien oder die Inseln des Malayischen Archipels, 1884–1894*.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Among indigenous figures, Soewardi Soerjaningrat was an early promoter of the name; in November 1918, he established the *Indonesisch Persbureau* in The Hague, a press bureau that used *Indonesia* in its name.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The Indonesian archipelago has been inhabited since prehistoric times.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Fossils of *Homo erectus* ("Java Man") date back between 2 million and 500,000 BCE, while *Homo sapiens* arrived around 50,000 BCE.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Archaeological discoveries include cave paintings in Sulawesi, where narrative rock art has been dated to at least 51,200 years ago.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Later megalithic traditions appeared in several regions, including Java, Sumatra, Sulawesi, Sumba, Flores, and Nias, where stone monuments were used for burial, ancestor veneration, commemoration, and ritual life.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Beginning several millennia BCE, peoples of the Austronesian language group migrated from Taiwan into island Southeast Asia, and related languages spread across much of the archipelago.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Rice cultivation and village life developed unevenly across the islands, while early trade in the last centuries BCE and the early centuries CE connected parts of the archipelago with South and East Asia.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Foreign merchants, goods, technologies, writing systems, and religious ideas entered local societies through these routes, helping some coastal settlements grow into ports and centres of local rule.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] From the 7th century, maritime kingdoms such as the Sumatra-based Srivijaya grew through trade and Buddhist religious networks.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Hindu and Buddhist influences also appeared in Javanese court culture, religious life, and temple architecture.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Between the 8th and 10th centuries, the Sailendra and Mataram dynasties built major architectural works, including Borobudur and Prambanan.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Following a failed Mongol invasion of Java, the Majapahit empire emerged in the late 13th century and came to dominate much of the archipelago's maritime commerce.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] These kingdoms and empires linked courts, ports, and religious communities across parts of the archipelago, although their authority varied by region and period.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Along the trade routes of the Indian Ocean and the Strait of Malacca, Islam was established in northern Sumatra by the late 13th century, and spread further through Java and Sumatra over the following centuries.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Historians have linked its expansion to maritime trade, the rise of coastal sultanates, and the work of Islamic teachers and missionaries, including the *Wali Sanga*.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In Java, older Javanese cultural forms entered Islamic practice, giving Javanese Islam a style unlike those found in Malaya and Sumatra.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] European entry into the archipelago began in the early 16th century, when Portuguese expeditions sought the eastern sources of the Asian spice trade.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Dutch voyages followed later in the century, and in 1602 competing Dutch trading companies were merged into the Dutch East India Company (*Verenigde Oostindische Compagnie*, VOC).
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The VOC began as a commercial company but acquired military, diplomatic, and territorial functions before it was dissolved in 1800, after which its possessions passed to the Dutch state as the Dutch East Indies.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Dutch rule expanded in stages and met repeated resistance, including in Java, Sumatra, Bali, and Aceh.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] During the late 19th and early 20th centuries, Dutch authority spread across several outer-island regions, bringing most of present-day Indonesia under colonial rule.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In western New Guinea, an early Dutch outpost was abandoned in the 1830s, and permanent occupation came only after 1898.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The resulting colony was governed from Batavia through centralised authority, with both direct rule and indirect arrangements across many local societies.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The Japanese invasion and occupation during World War II ended Dutch colonial rule; by 1945, Japan's impending defeat and surrender left nationalist leaders room to act.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] On 17 August 1945, shortly after Japan's surrender, Sukarno and Mohammad Hatta issued the Proclamation of Indonesian Independence; Sukarno later became the country's first president and Hatta its first vice-president.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The Netherlands then attempted to restore colonial rule, prompting the Indonesian National Revolution.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The conflict ended in 1949, when Indonesian resistance and pressure from the United Nations and the United States led the Netherlands to agree to a transfer of sovereignty.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Sukarno replaced parliamentary democracy with "Guided Democracy", concentrating authority around the presidency while balancing political Islam, the military, and the Communist Party of Indonesia (PKI).
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] After the attempted coup in 1965, the military blamed the PKI and, with allied civilian groups, carried out a widespread and violent anti-communist campaign.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The PKI was destroyed, Sukarno lost effective power, and Major General Suharto assumed the presidency in 1968, establishing the authoritarian New Order regime.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The new administration was supported by Western governments during the Cold War, reopened Indonesia to foreign investment, and governed during three decades of rapid economic growth and industrialisation.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia's invasion of East Timor in 1975 and the occupation that followed prompted international criticism, and the Santa Cruz massacre in 1991 put Indonesia's human-rights record under greater international scrutiny.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The Asian financial crisis in 1997–98 turned into a political crisis, causing unrest and Suharto's resignation in May 1998.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In 1999, East Timor voted to secede after nearly a quarter-century under Indonesian rule, a period discussed in scholarship in relation to genocide and occupation.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In the post-Suharto era, Indonesia introduced democratic reforms, including regional autonomy and the first direct presidential election.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The early years of reform also saw political instability, terrorism, and ethnic and religious conflict in several regions.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] A 2005 peace agreement ended large-scale fighting in Aceh after the previous year's Indian Ocean tsunami brought more international attention to the province.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Since the mid-2000s, Indonesia's economy has generally grown steadily, while its electoral democracy has endured, although corruption and criticism of authoritarian practices have persisted.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia is an equatorial archipelago of coastal plains, mountains, and volcanic islands.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] It lies between latitudes 11°S and 6°N and longitudes 95°E and 141°E, and is the world's largest archipelagic state, extending 5,120 kilometres (3,181 mi) from east to west and 1,760 kilometres (1,094 mi) from north to south.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Several straits, including Malacca, Sunda, and Lombok, carry international traffic between the Indian and Pacific Oceans, including ships transporting oil, gas, and industrial goods.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The number of Indonesian islands varies by counting method, with published figures ranging from 13,466 named islands to more than 17,500; about 922 are permanently inhabited.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Its five main islands are Sumatra, Java, Borneo (shared with Brunei and Malaysia), Sulawesi, and New Guinea (shared with Papua New Guinea).
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Java accounts for less than 7% of Indonesia's land area but is its most densely settled island, with intensive farming and extensive urban growth.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Forest cover also differs widely, with larger forested areas in Papua and Maluku than in Java and Bali.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia's terrain includes high peaks, volcanic lakes, major rivers, and coastal plains.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] At 4,884 metres (16,024 ft), Puncak Jaya in New Guinea is Indonesia's highest peak, while Lake Toba in Sumatra is its largest lake.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In Kalimantan, the Kapuas, Barito, and Mahakam form river networks that have long linked coastal and inland settlements.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Oceans, islands, monsoons, and topography affect rainfall; plate boundaries make earthquakes and volcanic eruptions frequent; and past changes in island connections have affected species distributions.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia's equatorial position and monsoon winds give it a tropical climate.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Most lowland areas are warm and humid throughout the year, while higher terrain is cooler; seasonal temperature differences are small.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Much of the country has a tropical rainforest climate, with tropical monsoon and savanna climates across parts of the islands.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The wet season usually runs from November to April and the dry season from May to October, although the timing differs by region.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Seasonal rainfall helps set rice-planting calendars and influences droughts, floods, and fires.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Western Sumatra, Java, and the interiors of Kalimantan and Papua are among the wetter areas, while regions nearer Australia, including Nusa Tenggara, are generally drier.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The surrounding oceans, island geography, monsoon winds, and topography all affect where and when rain falls.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In drier parts of the country, El Niño events can reduce rainfall and lengthen dry periods, causing water shortages and crop losses.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia is expected to face rising temperatures, changes in rainfall, higher sea levels, and greater exposure to heat and flooding.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] These changes affect agriculture, water supply, public health, coastal settlements, and wildfire management.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Sea-level rise is especially relevant to coastal areas, where much of Indonesia's population and infrastructure is located.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Poorer households and communities with weaker infrastructure are likely to have less capacity to adapt.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia lies on the Pacific Ring of Fire, where several major tectonic plates meet along subduction zones and active faults.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] It is one of the world's most active tectonic regions, with frequent earthquakes and volcanic eruptions.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Nearby communities face hazards from eruptions, lahars, ash fall, earthquakes, tsunamis, and other geological events.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] About 130 volcanoes are classified as active, with volcanism concentrated along the Sunda, Banda, and Halmahera arcs.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Fresh volcanic ash can damage crops, settlements, transport, and health, while weathered ash helps form fertile soils in volcanic regions, including parts of Java and Bali.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Large eruptions can also produce pyroclastic flows, lahars, volcanic tsunamis, and, in rare cases, affect climate and air travel beyond Indonesia.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Several eruptions in the archipelago have had effects far from their source.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] A super-eruption at present-day Lake Toba occurred around 74,000 years ago and has been examined for possible effects on climate and ancient human populations.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The eruption of Mount Tambora in 1815 had global climatic effects and contributed to the Year Without a Summer in 1816 across parts of the Northern Hemisphere.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The eruption of Krakatoa in 1883 caused severe regional destruction and drew worldwide scientific attention.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Earthquakes are frequent, especially along offshore subduction zones and active faults that cross the archipelago.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Offshore earthquakes can generate destructive tsunamis, while shallow inland and near-coastal earthquakes can heavily damage populated areas.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Major recent events include the 2004 earthquake and tsunami near northern Sumatra, the 2006 Yogyakarta earthquake, and the 2018 Sulawesi earthquake and tsunami.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia is one of 17 megadiverse countries recognised by Conservation International.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Its many islands, habitats, and geological history have produced a large number of plant and animal species, many found nowhere else.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Deep-water channels between islands have limited the movement of many species, leaving separate island lineages and high levels of endemism.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia's flora and fauna include Asian and Australasian species.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The Sunda Shelf islands have closer links to Asian fauna because lower sea levels once connected parts of western Indonesia with mainland Southeast Asia.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Farther east, Wallacea—including Sulawesi, Maluku, and the Lesser Sunda Islands—lies between the Sunda and Sahul shelves and has high endemism.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In western New Guinea, plate movement, changing island distances, and former land connections helped isolate microhylid frog lineages and diversify them.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia has 54,716 kilometres (33,999 miles) of coastline, with coastal and marine ecosystems that include coral reefs, mangroves, and seagrass beds.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Its reefs form part of the Coral Triangle and contain many coral and reef fish species.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia also contains most of Southeast Asia's old-growth forest.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Forest clearing and fragmentation continue to affect terrestrial habitats, while land-based pollution and destructive fishing have reduced coral diversity on some reefs.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia's major environmental pressures include peatland degradation, deforestation, logging, plantation expansion, and mining.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Peat swamp forests store large amounts of carbon and support distinct plant communities and threatened fauna, but logging, fire, drainage, and land conversion have reduced them.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] For many threatened species, including the critically endangered Bali myna, Sumatran orangutan, and Javan rhinoceros, the main pressures include habitat loss, habitat degradation, and illegal exploitation.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Forest fragmentation and land-use change break habitats into smaller blocks, isolate wildlife populations, and reduce biodiversity.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Conservation work includes protected areas, species and genetic conservation, forest and land rehabilitation, and community-based biodiversity management.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] As of 2024, Indonesia has designated 554 protected areas covering 27 million hectares, or 14% of its land area, along with marine reserves and 54 national parks.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Poaching, illegal logging, settlement expansion, tourism pressure, and non-timber cultivation still affect protected areas; implementation is also limited by weak local capacity, coordination, monitoring, and stakeholder participation.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Conservation measures can affect local rights and livelihoods, especially where stricter rules limit access to natural resources used for income.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia is a unitary republic with a presidential system under the 1945 Constitution.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The five principles of *Pancasila* appear in the preamble and are taught in civic education as the basis of Indonesian citizenship values.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] After the fall of the New Order in 1998, four constitutional amendments altered the political system by introducing direct presidential elections, creating new state institutions, reducing the MPR's role, and giving regional autonomy a constitutional basis.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia remained a unitary state, while decentralisation laws gave substantial powers to provinces, districts, and cities.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The president is head of state, head of government, and commander-in-chief of the Indonesian National Armed Forces, and may serve no more than two five-year terms.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The People's Consultative Assembly (*Majelis Permusyawaratan Rakyat*, MPR) consists of elected members of the House of Representatives (*Dewan Perwakilan Rakyat*, DPR) and the Regional Representative Council (*Dewan Perwakilan Daerah*, DPD).
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The MPR may amend the constitution, inaugurates the president and vice president, and may dismiss them under constitutional procedures.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The DPR makes laws with the president, approves the state budget, and oversees the government.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The DPD may propose, review, and advise on bills concerning regional government, but has less authority than the DPR.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Judicial power is held by the Supreme Court (*Mahkamah Agung*), the courts beneath it, and the Constitutional Court (*Mahkamah Konstitusi*).
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The Supreme Court is the final court for most civil and criminal cases and reviews regulations below the level of statutes.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The Constitutional Court reviews statutes against the constitution, settles conflicts between state institutions, rules on electoral disputes and petitions to dissolve political parties, and gives impeachment-related opinions.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The Religious Courts (*Pengadilan Agama*) hear Islamic family, inheritance, and certain Islamic economic cases for Muslims.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The Judicial Commission (*Komisi Yudisial*) proposes candidates for Supreme Court justices and has duties concerning judges' conduct.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Since the 1999 election, Indonesia has had a fragmented multi-party system.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] No party has won an outright majority in legislative elections, and presidents have usually governed through broad coalitions that include many parties in the legislature and cabinet.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Political parties are often grouped into secular-nationalist and Islamic-oriented parties, but governing coalitions commonly include both.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Party competition often relies more on patronage and elite bargaining than detailed policy programmes, although religious issues remain a source of ideological difference.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Opposition parties have at times joined presidential power-sharing arrangements after elections.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia held its first general election in 1955.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Since 2004, voters have directly elected the president, the DPR, and the DPD every five years.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Members of the DPR are elected through party-based contests, while DPD candidates run as individuals to represent provincial constituencies.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] National elections require large-scale logistics, as ballots and other materials must reach remote islands, mountain areas, and places with limited infrastructure.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia is a unitary state divided into provinces, regencies, and cities, each with elected regional authorities regulated by law.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Provinces are headed by governors and have provincial legislatures (*Dewan Perwakilan Rakyat Daerah*, DPRD).
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Regencies (*kabupaten*) and cities (*kota*) are headed by regents (*bupati*) and mayors (*wali kota*) and have local legislatures (*DPRD Kabupaten/Kota*).
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Governors, regents, mayors, and DPRD members are elected.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Regional autonomy after 1998 transferred substantial powers to subnational governments, especially regencies and cities.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Below regencies and cities are districts (*kecamatan*), which are divided into villages.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Rural villages (*desa*) have self-governing status, while urban villages (*kelurahan*) form part of district administration.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Special arrangements apply to nine provinces.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Aceh may implement aspects of Islamic law; Jakarta has autonomy at the provincial level because of its role as the national capital; and Yogyakarta retains a hereditary sultanate within the republican system.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In Papua, special autonomy includes the Papuan People's Assembly, which represents indigenous Papuans in cultural and rights-related matters.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia follows an "independent and active" (*bebas aktif*) foreign policy, a doctrine formulated by Mohammad Hatta in 1948.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In practice, the doctrine has meant avoiding military alliances and rival power blocs while using diplomacy to pursue national interests.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] As a middle power, Indonesia relies on regional diplomacy, multilateral forums, and flexibility in dealing with larger powers.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] As a founding member of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), Indonesia has made the organisation a main arena of its regional diplomacy.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] It has long supported Palestinian statehood and has no formal diplomatic relations with Israel, although informal contacts, visits, and trade links have existed.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In China–United States competition, Indonesia has avoided formal alignment with either power, supported ASEAN-led forums, and sought cooperation that does not heighten regional conflict.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia been a member of the United Nations since 1950, apart from a brief absence from the organisation in 1965–66.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] It participates in multilateral forums including the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM), the Organisation of Islamic Cooperation (OIC), and the East Asia Summit.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] After decades as a major recipient of foreign aid, Indonesia now also provides development assistance and established a foreign aid agency in 2019.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Since 1957, it has sent military and police personnel to UN peacekeeping missions, including Lebanon, the Democratic Republic of the Congo and Mali.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The Indonesian National Armed Forces (TNI) comprises the Army (TNI-AD), Navy (TNI-AL), including the Marine Corps, and Air Force (TNI-AU).
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Active personnel number about 300,400 in the Army, 65,000 in the Navy, and 30,100 in the Air Force.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The army developed out of the Indonesian National Revolution, and its leaders later claimed a political role because of their part in the struggle against Dutch rule.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The TNI also built a territorial command structure that runs from regional commands to local posts, linking it to internal security and local administration.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] During the New Order, the military held a formal political role under the doctrine of "dual function" (*dwifungsi*).
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Reforms after 1998 ended its formal parliamentary representation and removed it from day-to-day politics, but the territorial command system and off-budget military financing remained difficult to reform.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Military businesses, foundations, and other funding sources have long raised concerns about transparency and civilian oversight.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Defence spending has remained below 1% of GDP since 2007, and limited funding has pushed procurement toward foreign loans, second-hand equipment, and other lower-cost options.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Since independence, Indonesia has faced separatist movements and insurgencies, notably in Aceh and Papua.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The insurgency in Aceh ended after a 2005 peace agreement, while conflict has continued in Papua alongside special autonomy and security measures.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Reported abuses in Papua include torture, enforced disappearance, extrajudicial killing, arbitrary detention, and limits on assembly, expression, and the press.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Law enforcement in Indonesia is primarily carried out by the Indonesian National Police (POLRI).
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The Chief of the Indonesian National Police (*Kapolri*), is under and responsible to the President, and post-1998 reforms separated the police from the military and made it responsible for internal security and public order.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] POLRI's duties include maintaining public order and security, protecting and serving the public, and enforcing the law.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Human-rights concerns include anti-Chinese racism, Papuan protests against racist treatment, and communal violence after 1998, including conflicts in Kalimantan and Maluku.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Religious and gender minorities have faced discriminatory regulations, while anti-LGBT campaigns since 2016 have involved official statements, raids, and proposed legal restrictions.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The National Commission on Human Rights (*Komnas HAM*), established in 1993, is Indonesia's main state human-rights body and is authorised to promote, study, and investigate human-rights issues.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Its work has faced limits from internal disputes, politicisation, and non-cooperation from some state bodies, including the Attorney General's Office and the armed forces.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia has a mixed economy in which the private sector and the government both have large roles.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] It is the only G20 member state in Southeast Asia, has the region's largest economy by GDP, and ranks among the top 20 in nominal terms and the top 10 by purchasing power parity.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Services and industry account for the largest shares of gross domestic product, while agriculture remains a major source of employment.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The economy was once largely agricultural, and early post-independence policy centred on agricultural self-sufficiency.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Industrialisation and urbanisation began in the late 1960s and accelerated in the 1980s, after falling oil prices led the government to promote manufactured exports.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Manufacturing and non-oil exports grew in the 1980s and 1990s, during a period of rapid growth and falling poverty.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The Asian financial crisis in 1997–98 caused a severe contraction, followed by recovery and reforms in banking, public finance, and exchange-rate management.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Household consumption accounts for a large share of GDP, supported by Indonesia's population, urbanisation, and expanding consumer class.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Domestic demand helped soften the effect of the 2008 financial crisis, while exports, public spending, and private consumption contributed to the recovery after the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] However, many workers remain in informal jobs, and businesses face infrastructure, regulatory, and governance obstacles.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The archipelago's geography affects where economic activity takes place and how goods move across the country.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Inter-island transport and logistics costs are high, raising costs for production, investment, and the integration of regional markets.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Economic activity is concentrated on Java, while many outer regions have weaker infrastructure and less diversified local economies.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Tourism is a major service industry and source of foreign-currency earnings, though international tourism is concentrated in Bali and other major gateways.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Scientific and technological capacity has developed partly through state-backed strategic industries, including aircraft manufacturing and shipbuilding.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Transport policy focuses on connecting major corridors, islands, and remote regions, while energy policy covers fossil-fuel production, electricity supply, and the shift toward renewables.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Natural resources remain economically important.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Recent industrial policy has pushed for more domestic processing of raw materials, especially minerals such as nickel.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Extractive industries produce commodities such as coal, petroleum, and natural gas, while agricultural exports include palm oil, coffee, and spices.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The country also imports refined petroleum products and industrial inputs, and its major trade partners are primarily in Asia, alongside the United States.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia participates in regional and global economic arrangements, including ASEAN economic cooperation and APEC.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Cheaper imported inputs after tariff reductions helped raise manufacturing productivity and, in some districts, coincided with lower poverty.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Tourism is part of Indonesia's service economy, generating about US$14 billion in foreign-exchange earnings and recording 11.6 million international visitor arrivals in 2023.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] It supports jobs and businesses in accommodation, food services, transport, and related activities.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] International tourism is concentrated in Bali and other major gateways, while domestic travellers account for most tourism spending.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Expanding tourism beyond established destinations depends on better infrastructure, workforce skills, investment conditions, and environmental planning.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia has natural, cultural, and historical tourism sites across the archipelago.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Its UNESCO World Heritage Sites include Komodo National Park and the Cosmological Axis of Yogyakarta, while sites on the tentative list include Bunaken National Park and the Raja Ampat Islands.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Bali is the country's main destination for foreign tourists.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Historical and urban heritage tourism includes Dutch colonial sites in Jakarta and Semarang.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Research and development expenditure in Indonesia has historically remained a small share of GDP.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Its research and innovation system has low R&D spending, limited private-sector research, weak coordination among agencies, and uneven technology adoption.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Since the 1970s, Indonesia has used state-backed strategic industries to build domestic technological capacity.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesian Aerospace and PAL Indonesia have used technology transfer, licensed production, and foreign partnerships in aircraft manufacturing and shipbuilding.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] High costs, limited design capability, dependence on imported components, financing constraints, and small production scale continue to limit their competitiveness.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia established the National Institute of Aeronautics and Space (LAPAN) in 1963.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Satellite programmes have supported domestic communications, remote sensing, and maritime monitoring, including the use of Automatic Identification System data from LAPAN-A2 and LAPAN-A3 satellites.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] LAPAN also conducted suborbital rocket and propellant research in support of longer-term launcher development.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Transport in Indonesia serves a vast archipelago, while population and economic activity remain concentrated mainly on Java.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Roads carry most passenger and freight traffic; on many smaller and less developed islands, inter-island shipping and air transport provide access to major markets.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] High logistics costs, port bottlenecks, and uneven infrastructure make goods movement expensive, especially outside the main western islands.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Port availability and operations also affect internal trade and food-price gaps between provinces.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Land transport is most developed along the main population and economic corridors, especially on Java.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In cities, formal public transport often operates alongside smaller public and paratransit modes, including *bajaj*, *becak*, *angkot*, minibuses, and motorcycle taxis.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Public transport in many cities has not kept pace with urban growth, leading to heavy reliance on motorcycles and cars, while app-based ride-hailing has become part of daily travel.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Rail transport is concentrated on Java and Sumatra, with recent expansion into South Sulawesi.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In dense urban regions, commuter and rapid-transit systems include the Greater Jakarta commuter network, Jakarta MRT, and Palembang LRT.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In 2023, Indonesia opened its first high-speed rail line, *Whoosh*, linking Jakarta and Bandung through a project developed with China.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Maritime and air transport connect islands and long-distance routes beyond the main land corridors.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Air transport serves domestic and international travel, with Soekarno–Hatta International Airport as the country's main international gateway and Ngurah Rai and Juanda International Airport among other major airports.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Maritime transport is important to inter-island trade and logistics, with the Port of Tanjung Priok serving as the country's principal port and handling more than half of Indonesia's container traffic.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia produces more primary energy than it consumes.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In 2023, industry and transport accounted for 40% and 36% of final energy consumption, respectively.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Electricity supply is dominated by the state-owned State Electricity Company (*Perusahaan Listrik Negara*, PLN), which distributes power to most households and relies heavily on coal-fired generation.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Extending the grid is difficult in sparsely populated and island areas, while reliability problems are reported even in places connected to the grid.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia had 70.8 gigawatts (GW) of installed power generation capacity in 2023.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Coal is the largest source of primary energy consumption and electricity generation, with natural gas and petroleum also making large contributions.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Renewables account for a smaller share of supply, although Indonesia has large hydropower, solar, geothermal, wind, ocean, and bioenergy resources.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] It is also among the world's leading geothermal producers.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia exports energy commodities, including coal and liquefied natural gas, while importing refined petroleum products.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Although historically a leading LNG supplier, Indonesia has shifted more natural gas toward domestic use and gas-infrastructure expansion.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Energy policy therefore has to manage both commodity production and reliable power supply across the archipelago.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia has set targets to increase renewable energy use and reduce emissions, including a net-zero emissions goal by 2060 or sooner.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The transition is slowed by coal dependence, uncertain regulations, PLN's financial position, grid limits, and the cost of electrifying remote areas.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia has a large and unevenly distributed population.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The 2020 census recorded 270.2 million people, making Indonesia the world's fourth most populous country after India, China and the United States.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Its population size places heavy demand on jobs, housing, education, health care, and public services.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The population is concentrated on Java and in urban centres, while many provinces outside Java and Bali are far less densely settled.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Java is home to 56% of the population, making it the country's population centre.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Its population density is far above the national average, reaching 1,171 people per square kilometre (3,030 people/mi2).
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia has a median age of 31.5 years as of 2024 and a large working-age population.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Jakarta anchors the country's largest metropolitan area and, under the UN's harmonised urban definition, is listed as the world's most populous city, with nearly 42 million inhabitants as of 2025.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In the same year, approximately 59% of Indonesians lived in urban areas.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Urbanisation has come from rural-to-urban migration, natural increase in urban areas, and the reclassification of rural settlements.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] It has also expanded metropolitan regions, especially on Java, and increased demand for infrastructure, basic services, and city management.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] About 8 million Indonesians reside overseas, with large communities in Malaysia, the Netherlands, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, and Taiwan.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] A 2022 OECD report put the share of adults who intended to emigrate permanently at 2%, the lowest in ASEAN.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesian emigration is dominated by temporary labour migration, much of it to nearby or culturally and religiously familiar destinations such as Malaysia and Saudi Arabia.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The 2010 census listed over 1,300 *suku bangsa*, or ethnic groups; a later study reclassified them into about 600 groups after noting classification difficulties.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Austronesian-speaking populations predominate in much of western and central Indonesia; their spread across the islands involved migration, settlement, and mixing with older communities.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Melanesian populations live mainly in the eastern islands, including parts of Nusa Tenggara, Maluku, and western New Guinea.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The Javanese are the largest ethnic group, making up about 40% of the population.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] They have filled many senior roles in government and the military, in proportions somewhat above their share of the population, although their population share has declined.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Early Indonesian nationalists did not define the nation through a single ethnic tradition; they sought to accommodate ethnic difference within a united state.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Other major groups include the Sundanese, Malay, Batak, Madurese, Betawi, Minangkabau, and Bugis.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The official language, Indonesian, is a standardized variety of Malay based on the Riau-Johor literary tradition.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Malay had long served as a *lingua franca* in the archipelago before Indonesian nationalists adopted it as a language of unity through the 1928 Youth Pledge; it gained official status in 1945 under the name *Bahasa Indonesia*.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Written in the Latin script, Indonesian has spread through education, government, and mass media, and serves as a common language across ethnic and regional boundaries.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia is also one of the world's most linguistically diverse countries, with more than 700 languages spoken across the archipelago.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Most local languages belong to the Austronesian family, while eastern Indonesia includes more than 150 Papuan languages.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Javanese is the most widely spoken local language and has official regional status in Yogyakarta.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Several local languages also retain, or have historically used, distinct writing traditions.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Local languages remain part of regional identity and cultural heritage, even as Indonesian dominates national public life.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Colonial-era European-descended communities were small.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The 1930 census counted 246,000 Europeans in the Dutch East Indies, or 0.4% of the population, most of them Dutch nationals.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Dutch did not become widely spoken: Malay was already the main lingua franca, and colonial policy promoted Malay while Dutch-language education remained largely limited to Europeans and a small indigenous elite.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Dutch fluency today is limited, although the language is relevant to some civil and commercial codes whose official versions are still in Dutch.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia recognises six religions: Islam, Protestantism, Roman Catholicism, Hinduism, Buddhism, and Confucianism, while the constitution guarantees freedom to choose and practise religion and belief.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The state regulates religious affiliation and public worship.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Recognised religions receive administrative recognition for religious affiliation, marriages, and houses of worship, while followers of indigenous religions have often received weaker recognition or faced discrimination.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] *Pancasila* makes belief in one God one of the state ideology's five principles and is used to support national unity and religious harmony.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Religious minorities still face discrimination, including local religious bylaws, social pressure, and restrictions on worship.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia has more Muslims than any other country, with 251 million Muslims in 2025, or 87.15% of the population.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Protestants and Catholics together made up 10.44% of the population, and Christians form majorities in several eastern provinces.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Hindus accounted for 1.66% and are concentrated in Bali, while Buddhists accounted for 0.69% and are found mainly among Chinese Indonesians, though not exclusively.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Many local belief systems predate the recognised religions and continue alongside them.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] They include beliefs in ancestors, spirits, and powers tied to places such as fields, forests, rivers, and mountains.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Traditions such as Sunda Wiwitan, Kejawèn, and Kaharingan continue in different forms within or alongside the recognised religions.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In Java and Bali, Islam and Hinduism also absorbed older customs and ritual practices.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Hinduism and Buddhism were the earliest major religions from outside the archipelago to become established there.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indian religious and cultural influence entered through trade, intermarriage, and religious activity, and became part of palace culture and local practice.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Arabic geographers wrote about Southeast Asia by the 9th century, and Chinese records mention Muslim merchants and envoys by the 10th, while larger Muslim communities and polities developed from the late 13th century onward.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Islamisation unfolded through commerce, religious teachers, and the rise of Muslim port polities and sultanates.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Javanese traditions often present the *Wali Sanga* as the leading figures in the Islamisation of Java.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Christianity grew through Catholic and Protestant missions during the Portuguese and Dutch colonial periods, with different histories across regions and denominations.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] It became most established in parts of eastern Indonesia while remaining a national minority.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Small Jewish communities also existed in the archipelago, but their numbers have been negligible since Indonesian independence.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia's education system includes more than 50 million students and over 250,000 schools.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] It is managed across ministries responsible for school education, higher education, and religious education, and follows a 6-3-3-4 structure: six years of elementary school, three years each of junior and senior secondary school, and four years of tertiary education.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Since independence, schools have supported national integration through Indonesian-language instruction, national curricula, and civic education.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Access and school quality differ across regions, especially between urban and rural areas and between western and eastern provinces.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Net enrolment is highest at the primary level and lower at the secondary and tertiary levels.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Government spending on education accounted for approximately 1.3% of GDP in 2023.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In 2022, Indonesia had 4,481 higher education institutions, including universities, Islamic institutions, service colleges, and open universities.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The University of Indonesia, Gadjah Mada University, and the Bandung Institute of Technology are among the country's highest-ranked public universities in international rankings.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Higher education supplies skilled workers and supports research, but tertiary attainment, access, and institutional quality are uneven.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Remaining problems include unequal access, uneven infrastructure, teacher quality and distribution, and low learning outcomes for many students.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Student outcomes are generally stronger in urban and more developed areas than in many rural and disadvantaged areas.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] International assessments have also placed Indonesian students near the bottom in reading, mathematics, and science among participating economies.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] After independence, Indonesia began building a public health sector, but hospitals and other services faced severe resource shortages.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] The number of health facilities and workers later increased, although long travel times, uneven hospital access, and workforce gaps remain in several provinces.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] From the late 1960s, the government expanded basic healthcare through community health centres (*puskesmas*) in rural areas.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Routine immunisation began in the 1970s, and oral polio vaccine was added in 1981 under the expanded immunisation programme.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] In 2014, Indonesia launched *Jaminan Kesehatan Nasional* (JKN), a national health-insurance programme managed by the Social Security Agency on Health (*BPJS Kesehatan*).
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] JKN is one of the world's largest single-payer health-insurance systems and covered 98% of the population in 2024, but differences remain in service access, health-worker distribution, referrals, and specialist care.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Health expenditure was 2.69% of GDP in 2022.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Services are delivered through *puskesmas*, hospitals, and private providers.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Life expectancy rose from 54.9 years in 1973 to 71.1 years in 2023, while child mortality declined from 15.5 deaths per 100 live births in 1972 to 2.1 deaths in 2022.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia has also maintained polio-free status, although polio immunisation still requires sustained national and local support.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Indonesia faces a double burden of disease: non-communicable diseases account for a growing share of health loss, while communicable diseases remain a source of disability-adjusted life years.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Air pollution contributes to illness and health costs in Jakarta, and malaria elimination remains difficult in parts of eastern Indonesia.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p01] Other continuing problems include child stunting, which affected 21.6% of children under five according to 2022 data, and maternal mortality, which remains high compared with many neighbouring countries.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Indonesia's cultures differ across islands, languages, and communities.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Older populations and later Austronesian migrations contributed to this diversity, with Papuan and Melanesian populations prominent in the east.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Sea trade and migration linked the islands with India, Arabia, Persia, China, mainland Southeast Asia, and later Europe; these contacts brought religions, scripts, court arts, and colonial rule, often first through ports and trading towns.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Indonesia has no single uniform cultural tradition.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Regional arts and customs vary by local history, language, and community, while national forms use Indonesian and reach audiences across the country.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] These traditions include performance, visual art, ritual, clothing, food, and literature.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Modern popular culture includes cinema, television drama, music, celebrity media, and reality shows, along with imported Asian dramas and global formats adapted for Indonesian audiences.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Indonesia has 16 items on the UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage Lists, including wayang puppet theatre, batik, angklung, the saman dance, and pencak silat.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Recent joint nominations have added pantun, kebaya, and kolintang to the list.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Indonesian visual arts include textiles, puppetry, masks, carving, temple painting, and modern painting.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Many are part of ritual and court life, mark status or regional identity, and have changed with trade, colonial rule, nationalism, tourism, and urban art communities.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Among regional traditions, Balinese painting includes classical Kamasan and Wayang-style narrative forms.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Indonesian architecture ranges from everyday houses to ritual houses (*rumah adat*), whose layout, posts, roofs, heirlooms, and construction rites can mark ancestry, status, and local belief.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Regional forms include the Javanese *pendapa*, Dayak longhouses, Minangkabau *Rumah Gadang*, and Toraja *Tongkonan*.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Sculptural traditions include megalithic monuments in parts of Java, Sumatra, Sulawesi, Nias, Sumba, Flores, and other regions.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Ngaju Dayak *hampatong* figures have commemorative and protective functions, while Asmat artefacts are made for aesthetic and spiritual purposes.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Ancient Indonesian sculpture from the 8th to 15th centuries includes Hindu and Buddhist stone, bronze, and gold works.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Surviving temple architecture from the same period includes Borobudur and Prambanan.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Indonesian music and dance include court, village, ritual, and popular forms.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Gamelan traditions are centred especially in Java and Bali, while angklung and other bamboo ensembles are used in western Java, Banyumas, and other regions.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Drums, gongs, lutes, singing, and dance music also appear across the archipelago.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Islamic musical forms include gambus and qasida, while popular genres include keroncong and dangdut, which grew from Melayu music and draws on Indian, Arabic, and Western pop and rock elements.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Dance traditions serve different uses across regions.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Mask dances appear in Javanese court drama and Balinese ritual performance, while Dayak mask dances are performed in agricultural rituals and community ceremonies.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Javanese court dance includes forms such as *bedhaya* and *serimpi*, while other local dances accompany theatre, music, trance, healing, harvest, and rites of passage.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Younger performers also adapt global forms, including K-pop cover dance in Bali and hip-hop communities in Yogyakarta.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Clothing traditions differ by region and are used in ceremonies, weddings, formal occasions, and markers of local identity.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] *Batik* and *kebaya* are widely used in national and formal dress and are especially prominent in Javanese culture.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Other regional textiles and clothing traditions include the Batak ulos, Malay and Minangkabau songket, and Sasak ikat, which are used in ceremonies, weddings, exchange, and formal events.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Traditional Indonesian theatre uses storytelling, music, movement, puppetry, masks, and actor-dance.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] *Wayang* is a major puppet-theatre tradition in Java and Bali; many performances draw on the *Ramayana* and *Mahabharata*, are led by a *dalang*, and are accompanied by music.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Wayang has been used for ritual, moral instruction, comedy, political comment, and public messaging.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Other theatrical traditions include *Ludruk*, *Ketoprak*, *Sandiwara*, and *Lenong*.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] The Minangkabau *Randai* uses music, dance, drama, and martial arts (*silat*) to perform legends and historical narratives.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Balinese masked dance theatre, including *topeng*, has also been staged with modern stories and contemporary performance.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] In the modern period, theatre groups and networks, including *Teater Koma*, staged social criticism and political opposition during the late New Order period.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Indonesian cinema began during the Dutch colonial period with *Loetoeng Kasaroeng* (1926), and post-independence filmmaking developed through figures such as Usmar Ismail and Djamaluddin Malik.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] During the Sukarno era, film became part of nationalist and anti-colonial politics, while New Order cinema was subject to censorship, state regulation, and official histories.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] The large film industry of the 1970s and 1980s declined in the early 1990s.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] After 1998, low-budget independent films, film communities, festivals, and returning commercial producers revived the industry.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] *Kuldesak* (1999) helped launch this independent film movement, while *Ada Apa dengan Cinta?* (2002) showed the commercial reach of post-Suharto cinema.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Filmmakers addressed sexuality, city life, corruption, religion, and political memory, but state censorship, self-censorship, and pressure from non-state groups still limited expression.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] The Indonesian Film Festival (*Festival Film Indonesia*), first held in 1955, is the country's main national film-awards event.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Indonesian literature includes oral storytelling, inscriptions, court chronicles, religious texts, poetry, prose, and modern writing in Indonesian and regional languages.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Early writing used Indian-derived scripts and later Malay and Islamic literary forms, including Kawi, Jawi, *syair*, *pantun*, *hikayat*, and *babad*.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Well-known examples include *Hikayat Hang Tuah* in the Malay tradition and *Babad Tanah Jawi* in the Javanese tradition.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Modern Indonesian writing grew in the early 20th century through newspapers, Malay/Indonesian-language publishing, and the colonial publishing house *Balai Pustaka*.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Sumatran, especially Minangkabau, writers were prominent in early modern literature, while later figures such as Chairil Anwar, Pramoedya Ananta Toer, and Ayu Utami became prominent at different points in modern Indonesian literature.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Indonesian mass media has operated under state rules, commercial ownership, and changing communications technology.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] During the New Order, newspapers and broadcasters worked under licensing, censorship, and television policies that promoted development and official ideas of national culture.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] In the *Reformasi* era, the 1999 Press Law forbade censorship, press bans, and publication permits, but criminal and civil cases, political pressure, and attacks by private groups continued.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Internet use began in the early 1990s and grew quickly after 2000; by 2023, Indonesia had over 210 million internet users, helped by affordable smartphones and wider mobile-broadband coverage.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Mainstream outlets now use social-media distribution, shared newsrooms, shorter online formats, and cost-cutting.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Indonesian cuisine differs by island and region.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Local crops, fish, spices, religion, trade, and migration all affect what people cook and eat.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Food traditions use older local ingredients and techniques, along with later Indian, Chinese, Middle Eastern, Portuguese, Dutch, and other foreign influences.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Rice is the main staple food across much of the archipelago, usually consumed with side dishes of meat, fish, vegetables, and condiments.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Common ingredients and seasonings include chilli, coconut milk, shrimp paste, peanuts, garlic, shallots, tamarind, fish, and chicken.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Soy-based foods such as *tempeh* and *tahu* are also common, especially in Java and Bali.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Dishes such as *nasi goreng*, *gado-gado*, *mie*, and *sate* are consumed in many parts of the country.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Regional cuisines include Minangkabau dishes such as *rendang*.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] *Tumpeng*, a Javanese ceremonial rice dish, is used in rites of passage, thanksgiving, and public celebrations.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Indonesia has international sports such as football, badminton, weightlifting, and basketball, alongside local games and martial arts.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Football is one of the country's most followed sports, with active club supporters and public screenings of major matches.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Indonesia was the first Asian representative to appear at the FIFA World Cup, taking part in the 1938 tournament as the Dutch East Indies.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Badminton is one of Indonesia's most successful international sports.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Indonesia has won both the Thomas and Uber Cups, the world team championships of men's and women's badminton.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Most of Indonesia's Olympic medals have come from badminton and weightlifting.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Basketball also has a long organised history in the country, having appeared at the first National Sports Week in 1948 before the national basketball association was founded in 1951.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Local sports and games are used in ceremonies, harvest events, contests, and public entertainment.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] Examples include *sepak takraw*, bull racing (*karapan sapi*) in Madura, and ritual combat traditions such as *caci* in Flores and *pasola* in Sumba.
[src:indonesia/indonesia-p02] *Pencak silat* is an Indonesian martial art and was included as an official event at the 2018 Asian Games, where Indonesia won all fourteen gold medals contested in the sport.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] It was the only art institution established directly by the Non-Aligned Movement's decision.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] The Gallery was established on 1 September 1984 with the aim of collection, preservation and presentation of the arts and cultures of the non-aligned and developing countries.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] Over the years of its existence it acquired a collection of some 800 artworks from 56 non-aligned and developing countries.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] It contains "works of fine and applied art; furniture, musical instruments and other items of special importance; ethnological, anthropological, archaeological, geological and subjects related to significant events and historical figures; and antiques".
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] The gallery was formally closed on 4 April 1995 when the Parliament of Montenegro established the Centre for Contemporary Art of Montenegro which in full inherited the fundus of the "Josip Broz Tito" Art Gallery.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] Final document of the 7th Summit of the Non-Aligned Movement in New Delhi, India and the First Conference of Ministers of Culture of the Non-Aligned Movement, Pyongyang, North Korea, both in 1983, invited the member states to cooperate with the new gallery.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] Subsequent meeting of ministers of culture in Havana, Cuba proposed recognizing the gallery as a common institution.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] The "Josip Broz Tito" Art Gallery was established on 1 September 1984.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] The City of Titograd provided the representative Podgorica Royal Palace alongside the Morača river to host the gallery.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] In 1986 the gallery was recognized as a common institution of the NAM member states at the 8th Summit of the Non-Aligned Movement in Harare, Zimbabwe where the gallery organized exhibition as a part of the summit.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] This exhibition was subsequently presented in Lusaka, Dar es Salaam, Delhi and Cairo.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] That same year UNESCO supported organization of The First Symposium on Art and Development at the gallery.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] The gallery served as a common space to share at one place marginalized cultural production from the Third World countries and to counter hegemonic Eurocentrism in art and culture.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] Contrary to numerous museums and galleries in former colonial metropoles, the entire fundus of the gallery was formed from gifts and donations from the Non-Aligned member states.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] Bernard Matemera created his white marble sculpture called "Family" during his stay at the gallery in 1987.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] 1988 Non-Aligned Broadcasting Conference in Limassol, Cyprus decided to organize annual documentary TV competition at the gallery with 19 countries participating in 1988 and 20 countries in 1989.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] International status of the institution was officially recognized at the 9th Summit of the Non-Aligned Movement in Belgrade, SR Serbia in 1989.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] National selections of donations for the gallery were made either by foreign ministries or with the support of professional institutions with the notable case being Indian selection done with the support of the National Gallery of Modern Art from New Delhi.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] The Gallery presented a mummy called Nesmin from its Egyptian collection in the gallery from 1986 until 1991 when it was returned to the National Museum of Serbia in Belgrade on request of the Department of Archaeology at the Faculty of Philosophy, University of Belgrade.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] In 1995 the Parliament of Montenegro established the new Centre for Contemporary Art of Montenegro by merging the gallery with the Montenegrin Republic's Cultural Centre.
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] In September 2024, the Administration for the Protection of Cultural Property of Montenegro granted the gallery and collection the "status of movable cultural property of national importance".
[src:indonesia/josip-broz-tito-art-gallery-of-the-nonaligned-countries] This decision came as a result of a successful initiative by the curators of the then Contemporary Art Center (Marina Šaranović, Anita Ćulafić, Nađa Baković and Natalija Vujošević) who made the request in 2022.
